	volume			= {Day 2 Tue, May 07, 2024},
	pages			= {D021S027R006},
	organization	= {},
	address			= {},
	speid			= {},
	doi				= {10.4043/35408-MS},
	url				= {https://doi.org/10.4043/35408-MS},
	href			= {https://onepetro.org/OTCONF/proceedings-pdf/24OTC/2-24OTC/D021S027R006/3403366/otc-35408-ms.pdf},
	note			= {},
	logline			= {},
	abstract		= {Deepwater Emergency Pipeline Repair Systems (EPRS) are a suite of dedicated equipment manufactured, tested, and stored for the full life of the pipeline(s) in readiness to quickly perform a repair in the event of damage to the pipeline occurring. The requirement, design, manufacture, and storage of these systems carry Commercial and Technical challenges.  An overview of an EPRS will first be provided, followed by a review of the associated Commercial Challenges. Following this an outline of the Technical Challenges and Technical Drivers (decisions made by the design team which drive the direction of the system design) are discussed. Finally, three pipeline repair system case studies will be presented.  The requirement for an EPRS can range from it being a legislative requirement, a governmental license requirement, a commercial, reputational and environmental consideration, a requirement of the pipeline operators insurers, all focused on limiting loss of oil and gas transport volume should a breach of pipeline integrity occur. Considerations are often aided by detailed Front End Engineering Design (FEED) studies and can be supported by a pipeline operator consortium to share costs in a given geographical region.  The Technical Challenges are external factors, generally fixed parameters such as pipeline diameter, operating pressure or environment, and are not readily influenced by the EPRS designer. The EPRS Technical Drivers must accommodate all aspects of the pipelines performance envelope, but can be delivered by a range of different solutions optimised, technically and commercially, to fulfilling the specified scope. These drivers will be described further in this paper along with respective, technical, and commercial options.  This paper addresses three EPRS solutions that have been built: one deployed in West Africa, one currently stored in North West Australia in readiness for a repair and one built and tested for the Black Sea region.  This overview of the key challenges associated with a repair system, and how these have been solved on the three EPRS case studies, will provide valuable information to pipeline operators considering a Deepwater EPRS solution.}
}

@inproceedings{ref:affonso2024a,
	author			= {Affonso, I. D. and Rodrigues, L. T. and Queiroz, J. L. and Vieira, P. F. and Castelli, L. C. and Moreira, P. C. and Rocha, A. O. and Silva, A. C. and Zeilmann, R. P.},
