	note			= {},
	logline			= {},
	abstract		= {This paper presents a multidisciplinary view of the evolution in the concept of a development project for the central area of Sururu and the method applied to address the challenges and propose solutions for the project in progress.  The central area of Sururu reservoir presents distinct characteristics from typical Brazilian Presalt fields, with low permeabilities despite of high porosity. This context brings challenges to define the best production development plan for the area, since its reservoir features, with low productivities, make conventional Presalt development architectures not suitable.  To support the production development strategy, an extensive but budget-oriented appraisal plan was carried out, including an early production system connecting one well to an existing Floating Production Storage and Offloading ({FPSO}). This data acquisition effort was extremely important to enable an evaluation of the long-term productivity as well as a better understanding and dynamic characterization of the reservoir.  As a natural outcome of this comprehensive appraisal plan, the project base case has undergone drastic conceptual changes during its evolution, from a first concept including a stand-alone Floating Production Unit (FPU) to drain the area, to the current production strategy, comprising a reduced number of wells to be connected through a long tie-back to an infrastructure already installed in the area.  The current development solution comprises a manifold with four production wells connected to it and a subsea Multiphase Pump (MPP) to lift the fluids. To improve reservoir management in this shared production configuration and allow production allocation, one Multiphase Flow Meter (MPFM) for each production well will be included in the manifold. The drainage system also contains a water injection well to support the reservoir pressure, in a reversed five-spot configuration.  Gathering the wells, flowrates at a manifolded system are higher than conventional satellite configuration and contribute to reduce some flow assurance risks. Moreover, a Hydrate Mitigation Cross-Over (HMXO) equipment allowing the connection between service and production lines at the riser base will be installed to reduce hydrate issues.  The low productivity and the decreasing reservoir pressure mean that artificial lift is mandatory. Subsea multiphase boosting will bring an increment in production due to the favorable conditions for this type of technology and to the limitation of gas processing in the existing {FPSO}, which will reduce the gas available for gas lift.  The appraisal, project optimization and non-conventional technologies for the Brazilian Presalt environment have allowed Petrobras and its partners to point out a promising production development solution which reduces risks and improves economic results in a highly challenging reservoir environment.}
}

