	doi				= {10.4043/35470-MS},
	url				= {https://doi.org/10.4043/35470-MS},
	href			= {https://onepetro.org/OTCONF/proceedings-pdf/24OTC/3-24OTC/D031S041R007/3403091/otc-35470-ms.pdf},
	note			= {},
	logline			= {},
	abstract		= {The Lufeng 22-1 oil field is in the South China Sea, at a water depth of approximately 330 m. It was first developed with a floating production storage and offloading ({FPSO}) unit, subsea wells, and the first electrical submersible pump in the industry, moving subsea processing a giant step forward. After producing for 12 years, it became China’s first abandoned offshore field.  Recently, the field had its first oil for the second time, when the owner re-developed the same field using a different concept with a 19-km subsea tieback and new subsea boosting technology. In combination with an offshore platform, it enabled the economic development of the area for marginal fields.  The paper begins with a discussion of the development challenges of this field, and provides a holistic review of different development options, including a standalone development vs. a tieback development. It was pioneering act to adopt the first subsea boosting system, which has advanced significantly over the last two decades. In the past, the field was initially developed using five subsea pumps, with one for each subsea well. However, as a result of significant technological advances and maturation in the years since, it was more recently redeveloped using a single pump to process all flows. The comparison of the two development concepts allows for a rare opportunity to assess the impact of the technology advancement over time. The values brought by the technology are analyzed from both technical and operational point of view.  The re-adoption of the subsea boosting technology with a subsea tieback is of great significance to the offshore field development in China, where many marginal fields and long tieback fields can be enabled.}
}

@inproceedings{ref:garrote2024a,
