	href			= {https://onepetro.org/OTCONF/proceedings-pdf/24OTC/3-24OTC/D031S034R005/3400476/otc-35181-ms.pdf},
	note			= {},
	logline			= {},
	abstract		= {Subsea production field development is an evolving process. This paper describes subsea power and communications distribution network solutions that are designed for life of field and can be configured to meet the evolving needs of a production field. It also highlights the capabilities and limitations of such solutions to facilitate its application with the goal of minimizing capital expense and maximizing performance and reliability.  Leveraging the design and flexible configurability of deployed product, a novel design has been established to make the product suitable for brownfield applications. The product design has been reviewed and matured from three key aspects \textendash{} signal analysis, hardware prototyping and communications testing. For analysis, models have been developed in tool (ORCAD) to determine the performance capability of the novel design. Hardware prototyping and API 17F Q1/Q2 tests establishes the reliability benchmark. Lab based communication bench tests provides insights on data transfer and integrity such that boundary conditions are established. Holistic requirements-based testing, based on experience of deployed product, is key to successful launching of novel design.  Early analysis revealed areas to improve the design margin when applied in novel design. Analysis also highlighted areas that can be further utilized beyond current capability of the product. Hardware prototype is built to determine the packaging in subsea modules and functional performance. Functional performance is determined using API Q1 tests and Q2 tests are executed to understand the design margin when physical stress(es) is applied. Lab based bench tests revealed communication performance and established data related specifications for the novel design. Assimilating the results has allowed the boundary conditions to be established for which the product is deemed suitable in multiple applications. Successful implementation of the product allows it to be applied in greenfield and brownfield opportunities. Novel design implementation enabled leveraging existing equipment and not require significant investments on new umbilicals in extending or tied back of production fields. It also shall allow phased introduction of well by leveraging the switching feature (controlled from Topside) in the module.  The paper discusses flexibility aspect (multiple configurations) of the product and touches upon how it is leveraged for brownfield application with a novel design. Using same building blocks of an existing product in multiple applications allows to accelerate reliability growth and benefit the industry.}
}

@inproceedings{ref:serra2024a,
